Why killing fossil fuels won't kill plastic
Ending fossil fuel extraction would raise plastic costs but almost certainly not solve the plastic pollution crisis. The relationship between decarbonization and plastic production is real — 60–70% of virgin plastic production cost comes from fossil fuel feedstock — yet a web of counteracting forces (the petrochemical pivot, coal-to-chemicals, waste management failures, and billions of tonnes of legacy pollution) means the energy transition alone is insufficient. Under the most aggressive decarbonization scenarios modeled by the IEA and OECD, petrochemicals become the last bastion of oil demand, not its casualty. Plastics would get more expensive, perhaps doubling in cost, but demand modeling suggests this would cut consumption by only about a third, concentrated in disposable packaging rather than the medical, construction, and industrial applications where plastic is functionally irreplaceable. The deeper problem is that plastic pollution is driven not primarily by production volume but by waste management collapse in the Global South, a challenge that costlier plastic does nothing to fix.
Fossil fuels subsidize every plastic bag, bottle, and pipe you touch
The economic entanglement between fossil fuels and plastic runs deep. Petrochemical feedstock accounts for 12–14% of global oil demand today, a share the IEA projects will rise to 17.4% by 2030 — roughly one in every six barrels. An additional 8% of natural gas goes to petrochemical production. For a typical naphtha steam cracker — the workhorse of European and Asian plastic production — feedstock costs represent roughly 60–70% of total production costs, with capital expenditure contributing only about 13%. This makes plastic prices exquisitely sensitive to oil and gas prices: when crude rises, resin follows.
The result is that virgin plastic is astonishingly cheap. Commodity polyethylene and polypropylene trade at roughly $900–$1,300 per tonne depending on region and grade, having fallen 30–44% from 2021 pandemic-era peaks. This cheapness is the root economic cause of plastic pollution: when a material costs less than a dollar per kilogram, there is no incentive to recover it. Recycled HDPE in the United States costs approximately $1,631 per tonne versus $943 for virgin — a 73% penalty for choosing the sustainable option. In a world where virgin plastic is this cheap, recycling cannot compete on economics alone.
Global plastic production reached approximately 436 million metric tonnes in 2023, with 90.4% derived from fossil fuels. Production has doubled since 2000 and, under business-as-usual projections, the OECD expects it to nearly triple to 1,231 million tonnes by 2060. If fossil fuel extraction were dramatically curtailed, this feedstock dependency would eventually force prices upward — but the timeline and magnitude of that effect depend on several complicating factors.
Oil companies are betting their futures on plastic, not abandoning it
The "petrochemical pivot" is not a theory — it is the declared corporate strategy of the world's largest oil companies. Saudi Aramco acquired a 70% stake in SABIC for $69.1 billion and is pursuing an explicit "liquids-to-chemicals" strategy to maximize crude-to-chemicals conversion. ExxonMobil plans to invest over $20 billion expanding plastic production and built a 1.8-million-tonne-per-year ethylene cracker on the Gulf Coast. Shell completed a $6 billion ethane cracker in Pennsylvania. ADNOC and OMV merged petrochemical assets into Borouge Group International, valued at approximately $60 billion. Collectively, over $200 billion has been invested in 333 plastic and chemical projects in the United States alone since 2010.
The IEA has stated plainly that "petrochemicals are set to be the largest driver of world oil demand" — larger than trucks, aviation, and shipping combined. In the agency's Net Zero Emissions by 2050 scenario, where total oil demand falls 75%, petrochemicals become 55–70% of all remaining oil consumption. Oil demand for petrochemical feedstock is the only segment that grows even under the most aggressive climate policy. This means the energy transition doesn't starve plastics of feedstock — it concentrates the remaining fossil fuel industry around them.
The result is a paradox: the very forces driving decarbonization are simultaneously driving petrochemical overcapacity. Between 2020 and 2025, global ethylene capacity expanded by more than 40 million tonnes, roughly 70% of it in China. China's polypropylene capacity surged from 20 million tonnes in 2015 to 48 million tonnes in 2024. Global excess capacity for six major chemical building blocks hit 218 million tonnes in 2023 — nearly triple the 2000–2022 average. Polyethylene cash margins have been largely negative since mid-2022. This glut is pushing virgin plastic prices down, making recycled and bio-based alternatives even less competitive — the opposite of what decarbonization advocates hope for.
No alternative feedstock can match fossil plastic on cost or scale
If fossil feedstocks vanished, the replacement options range from moderately expensive to prohibitively costly. The cheapest alternative is bio-based polyethylene from sugarcane (produced commercially by Braskem in Brazil), which carries a 30–50% price premium over fossil PE. But Braskem's entire capacity is just 260,000 tonnes per year — 0.06% of global demand. Scaling bio-PE to replace 430 million tonnes of fossil-based production would require roughly 200 million hectares of sugarcane or corn, approximately equal to all current global sugarcane and corn acreage combined.
PLA (polylactic acid) from corn starch costs $2,000–$3,125 per tonne — an 80–160% premium — and has performance limitations including temperature sensitivity. PHA bioplastics cost $4,000–$6,000 per tonne, representing a 200–400% markup. Total global bioplastic production in 2025 was just 1.67 million tonnes, roughly 0.5% of conventional plastic output. Even optimistic projections from European Bioplastics see capacity reaching only 4.69 million tonnes by 2030 — barely 1% of global need.
The most technologically ambitious pathway — making plastics from green hydrogen and captured CO₂ via methanol-to-olefins — costs €2,500–€3,500+ per tonne of high-value chemicals, representing a 180–340% premium over fossil-based production. According to ING Research, CO₂ prices would need to reach an unrealistic €1,000–€1,600 per tonne to bring fossil plastic costs up to green hydrogen plastic levels. A 2025 SYSTEMIQ analysis found that fossil-free plastics can match "abated" fossil production costs (fossil plastics with full carbon pricing and CCS), but not today's unabated prices.
The bottom line from cost analysis: if fossil feedstocks were eliminated, the average price of plastic would likely double across the product mix, with some applications seeing 3–4× increases. The green premium clusters around 50–100% above fossil baseline for the most realistic alternatives.
A 30% demand drop, not an end to plastic
Would costlier plastic actually reduce pollution? OECD modeling provides the most rigorous answer. Their "Global Ambition" scenario applies a tax of $750 per tonne by 2030, rising to $1,500 per tonne by 2060 — effectively doubling to tripling the price of plastic. The result is a one-third reduction in plastic use below baseline, implying a long-run price elasticity of roughly -0.3 to -0.5. That is meaningful but far from elimination.
The response would be highly uneven across sectors. Packaging, which represents 36–42% of all plastic use, is the most price-elastic segment. Ireland's €0.15 plastic bag tax produced a 90% reduction in bag use almost overnight. Uruguay saw 70–85% drops in disposable bag demand when pricing was introduced. Single-use consumer goods, disposable cutlery, and fast-fashion synthetic textiles would similarly respond to significant price increases.
But roughly 35–40% of plastic use is in long-lived, functionally critical applications where demand is deeply inelastic. Medical plastics — a $26.78 billion market in 2024, growing at 6.6% annually — include syringes, IV bags, sterile packaging, and implants for which material substitution requires full regulatory requalification adding years and enormous costs. Construction (PVC pipes, insulation), automotive (lightweighting for fuel efficiency and safety), aerospace composites, electronics, and increasingly clean energy technology (solar panels, wind turbine blades, EV battery components) all depend on plastics with no cost-competitive substitutes at comparable performance levels. Even the IEA's Clean Technology Scenario acknowledges that "the limited availability of cost-effective substitutes for oil feedstock means that oil demand for petrochemicals remains resilient."
What the major institutions actually project
The consensus across major research bodies is that decarbonization constrains but does not eliminate plastic production, and that dedicated plastics policy is essential.
The IEA's Net Zero by 2050 scenario sees total oil demand plummet to 24 million barrels per day by 2050, but petrochemical feedstock demand actually increases by 1.5 mb/d to 2030, and by 2050 petrochemicals consume 55% of all remaining oil. Carbon Tracker's 2024 "Petrochemical Imbalance" report warns of $400 billion in planned capacity at risk of becoming stranded assets, while noting that virgin plastic demand could peak by 2027 if circular economy policies accelerate — but that achieving this requires active intervention, not just energy transition.
CIEL's analysis is the most direct: 99% of plastics are fossil-derived, and 90% of their lifecycle greenhouse gas emissions come from production, not disposal. They project that plastics could consume 13% or more of Earth's remaining 1.5°C carbon budget if expansion plans proceed. SYSTEMIQ's "Breaking the Plastic Wave 2025" update finds that without intervention, plastic pollution will jump from 130 to 280 million tonnes by 2040, and that existing solutions can cut pollution by 83% — but only through coordinated action across reduction, redesign, recycling, and waste management, not through upstream energy policy alone.
The OECD's most ambitious scenario achieves near-elimination of plastic leakage by 2040 through lifecycle policies at an additional cost of just $50 billion. But their modeling shows that even this scenario still produces 440–810 million tonnes of plastic per year by 2060. The UN Global Plastics Treaty, which could have mandated production caps, failed to reach agreement at both INC-5.1 (December 2024) and INC-5.2 (August 2025), with oil-producing nations blocking binding production limits.
Five reasons the energy transition alone falls short
The most important counterargument is that alternative feedstocks already exist at scale. China produces 16% of its petrochemicals from coal as of 2018, with 76% of its PVC output coal-based. Over 50 coal-to-chemical projects are under consideration, and China's 14th Five-Year Plan explicitly exempts chemical-feedstock coal from energy intensity targets. If oil and gas become scarce, coal-to-olefins technology is commercially proven and could sustain plastic production — albeit with even worse climate consequences unless paired with carbon capture.
Second, the timeline mismatch is severe. Even aggressive decarbonization unfolds over decades. Meanwhile, OECD projections show production reaching 736 million tonnes by 2040 under current policy, meaning an additional 6–8 billion tonnes of plastic will be produced before any fossil fuel phase-out could meaningfully constrain feedstock. This roughly equals the entire cumulative output of the previous 70 years.
Third, legacy pollution persists regardless of new production. Approximately 9.2 billion tonnes of plastic have been produced since 1950, with 79% ending up in landfills or the environment. Some 30 million tonnes sit in the oceans and 109 million tonnes have accumulated in rivers, ensuring continued ocean leakage for decades even if all new mismanagement stopped. Microplastic emissions of 10–40 million tonnes per year will continue increasing from fragmentation of existing debris even if production halted entirely.
Fourth, waste management failure is the proximate cause of pollution, not production volume. Seventy percent of environmental plastic leakage comes from just 20 countries with inadequate waste infrastructure. OECD countries account for only 11% of macroplastic leakage despite consuming far more plastic per capita. Making plastic more expensive does not build collection systems in Lagos, Jakarta, or Mumbai — it may simply make food packaging and medical supplies less affordable for the world's poorest populations.
Fifth, the petrochemical pivot creates perverse incentives. As transport fuel demand peaks (possibly as early as 2025–2027), oil companies are redeploying capital into petrochemicals at unprecedented scale. Carbon Tracker notes that to offset declining transport demand, petrochemical output would need to grow at 3.9% annually to 2035. The massive overcapacity already built ensures that virgin plastic remains cheap for years, regardless of what happens to energy markets.
Conclusion
The thesis that ending fossil fuels would solve plastic pollution contains an important economic insight — fossil feedstocks do make plastic artificially cheap — wrapped in a dangerous oversimplification. Decarbonization would raise plastic prices, perhaps doubling them, which would meaningfully reduce single-use packaging (roughly 40% of production) while barely denting demand in medical, construction, and industrial applications. But three structural realities undermine the thesis fatally: oil companies are racing to lock in petrochemical capacity before energy demand peaks; coal and biomass can substitute as feedstocks; and the 9.2 billion tonnes of plastic already in the environment will keep fragmenting and polluting for centuries. The most rigorous modeling from the OECD, IEA, and SYSTEMIQ converges on the same conclusion: solving plastic pollution requires direct, dedicated plastics policy — production caps, extended producer responsibility, recycled content mandates, waste infrastructure investment, and international treaty obligations — not just the indirect effects of an energy transition that the fossil fuel industry is already maneuvering to survive.
The Broken Supply Chain: Deep Research on Cocoa, Coffee, and Palm Oil
A critical examination of three commodity supply chains that shape landscapes, livelihoods, and consumer ethics

PART I: COCOA & CHOCOLATE
1. Child Labor in West African Cocoa: The Numbers
The scale of child labor in West African cocoa remains staggering after more than two decades of international attention. The most comprehensive recent data comes from the NORC study at the University of Chicago, published in October 2020 and funded by the U.S. Department of Labor's Bureau of International Labor Affairs.
Key findings from the NORC 2020 report:
An estimated 1.56 million children were engaged in cocoa production in Côte d'Ivoire and Ghana during the 2018-19 harvest season — approximately 790,000 in Côte d'Ivoire and 770,000 in Ghana.
Of those, approximately 1.48 million were exposed to at least one component of hazardous child labor.
Hazardous child labor in cocoa production increased by 13 percentage points over a 10-year period (2008-09 to 2018-19), coinciding with a 62% growth in cocoa production across both countries.
The proportion of children exposed to agro-chemicals increased roughly fivefold — from 5% to 24% between 2008-09 and 2018-19.
Children were most commonly exposed to sharp tools, heavy loads, and agro-chemical products.
Nearly every third child living in an agricultural household in the two countries was engaged in hazardous cocoa work.
The geographic expansion problem: NORC researcher Kareem Kysia noted that as cocoa production expanded dramatically, farming spread into areas where infrastructure to monitor child labor was weak and awareness of laws was low. Hazardous child labor increased substantially in low and medium production areas — precisely the regions with the least NGO and corporate intervention coverage.
The methodological controversy: Earlier Tulane University surveys (2008-09, 2013-14) had estimated even higher numbers — 2.26 million children working in cocoa production by 2013-14. However, an independent Expert Group commissioned to review methodology discovered that weightings had been incorrectly applied in previous surveys, inflating estimates. This means while the 1.56 million figure is the best current estimate, decade-over-decade comparisons are unreliable.
COVID-19 impact: NGOs including Mighty Earth, Be Slavery Free, and Green America have argued the NORC data is already outdated, claiming an estimated 15-20% increase in child labor during the pandemic due to deteriorating economic conditions.
The 2024 update: As of 2024, the U.S. Department of Labor's ILAB List of Goods Made with Child Labor and Forced Labor still includes cocoa. The governments of Ghana and Côte d'Ivoire, together with the World Cocoa Foundation and the U.S. Department of Labor, signed a new 2024-2029 Framework of Action aimed at scaling solutions — the latest in a series of frameworks that have followed each missed deadline.

2. The Harkin-Engel Protocol: A 25-Year Autopsy
The Harkin-Engel Protocol, signed in September 2001 by the Chocolate Manufacturers Association and the World Cocoa Foundation (witnessed by U.S. Senator Tom Harkin and Representative Eliot Engel), was a voluntary industry commitment to eliminate the worst forms of child labor in the cocoa sectors of Ghana and Côte d'Ivoire.
What was promised:
A child-labor-free certification process covering 50% of cocoa-growing regions by 2005 and 100% by the end of 2010.
Industry-wide standards for public certification.
What happened — a timeline of failure:
2005: The original deadline was missed entirely. The target was pushed to 2008.
2008: Missed again. Reset to 2010.
2010: Tulane University's Payson Center audit found efforts "have not even come close to these targets" and that "hundreds of thousands of children are involved in work on cocoa farms." The protocol was restructured into a Declaration of Joint Action with a new goal: a 70% reduction in the worst forms of child labor by 2020.
2015: Tulane's final major survey found a 21% increase in the total number of children working in cocoa and an 18% increase in hazardous work from 2008-09 to 2013-14.
2020: The NORC study found 1.56 million children still in cocoa production with hazardous work rates increasing. The World Cocoa Foundation pledged (again) to eliminate child labor. The 70% reduction target was not met.
2024: A new 2024-2029 Framework of Action signed — effectively the fourth reset in 25 years.
The structural critique: The protocol was a voluntary commitment designed to prevent federal legislation mandating labeling and accountability. It succeeded spectacularly at that narrow political goal — no binding legislation was ever passed — while failing at its stated humanitarian purpose. As one coalition of NGOs put it, the chocolate industry has been "more interested in public relations than real solutions." The global chocolate confectionery market generates over $100 billion annually in retail sales, while most cocoa farmers earn less than $1 per day and the industry's collective sustainability investments have remained a small fraction of revenues.

3. Agroforestry vs. Monoculture Cocoa
A landmark 2020 meta-analysis of 52 articles directly comparing cocoa agroforestry and monoculture systems (published in Environmental Research Letters) produced definitive findings:
Yields: Cocoa-specific yields in agroforestry systems were approximately 25% lower than in monocultures. However, total system yields — including fruits, timber, and other crops — were approximately 10 times higher.
Carbon storage: Agroforestry systems stored 2.5 times more carbon than monocultures, making them a significant climate change mitigation tool.
Climate adaptation: Agroforestry lowered mean temperatures and buffered temperature extremes, creating more favorable microclimates for cocoa trees — critical as West Africa faces rising temperatures.
Profitability: Despite lower cocoa-specific yields, the two systems showed similar overall profitability because agroforestry income is diversified across multiple products.
Biodiversity: The limited available studies showed higher biodiversity in agroforestry systems.
Soil: No significant differences in main soil parameters between systems.
The barriers to adoption: Despite these advantages, the transition faces serious obstacles. Most cocoa farmers in Côte d'Ivoire (the world's largest producer) still cultivate in monocultures. Farmers earning less than $1/day cannot afford the initial investment to transition. Land and tree tenure insecurity prevent long-term planning. New cocoa varieties have been bred for full-sun conditions. And corporate agroforestry standards remain weak — many companies promote simple tree-planting schemes that look good in sustainability reports but deliver minimal ecological benefit. The Mighty Earth/Voice Network critique found that companies often give away tree seedlings that are never planted or don't survive in established monocultures, allowing more plantations to be certified as "agroforestry" without meaningful improvement.

4. Fair Trade Cocoa: Models and Critiques
The Tony's Chocolonely model: Founded by Dutch journalist Teun van de Keuken, Tony's operates on "5 Sourcing Principles" — traceable beans, higher prices, stronger farmers, long-term commitment, and improving quality and productivity. As of their 2024-2025 annual report:
32,133 farmers benefited from their sourcing principles (a 58% increase year-over-year).
The company achieved €200 million in revenue with 33% growth.
99.9% of their cocoa is verified deforestation-free.
Tony's pays both the Fairtrade premium and an additional Tony's premium, using a Living Income Reference Price model developed jointly with Fairtrade.
Their "Open Chain" model allows other brands to source ethically through Tony's supply chain. Over 20 "Mission Allies" now participate.
Traditional Fairtrade: Fairtrade certification guarantees a minimum floor price plus a premium (~$240/tonne) for community development. The critique: the premium is modest relative to the scale of poverty, the certification process is costly for small cooperatives, and the floor price hasn't kept pace with living income calculations.
Direct trade: Bean-to-bar and specialty chocolate makers often prefer direct trade, building relationships with specific cooperatives and paying well above market rates. The advantage is transparency and relationship depth. The critique: it works at boutique scale but cannot transform the system for the millions of farmers supplying mass-market chocolate.
Cooperative-grown models: Divine Chocolate represents an alternative where Kuapa Kokoo, a Ghanaian cocoa farmers' cooperative, holds a 45% equity stake in the company. This ownership model means farmers benefit from company profits, not just price premiums — resulting in £2 million invested in schools, wells, and clinics throughout Ghana. Research shows that firms with farmer equity ownership tackle wider social and environmental issues regardless of market willingness to pay premiums, while firms without farmer ownership limit their social investments to what the market rewards.
The overarching critique: The root cause is structural. Cocoa farmers receive a tiny fraction of the value chain. Even Fairtrade coffee research shows farmers receive approximately one-sixth of the consumer premium. Industry pledges of $500 million+ sound impressive but represent a fraction of $100+ billion annual industry revenues. Living income benchmarks remain unmet for the vast majority of farmers regardless of certification scheme.

5. Bean-to-Bar: Revolution or Luxury?
The bean-to-bar movement, which took off around 2010, now represents a market estimated at $4.34 billion (2025) growing at 7.24% annually, projected to reach $6.16 billion by 2030. Several hundred small manufacturers operate globally.
What it does well:
Creates unprecedented transparency — makers visit farms, know their farmers, and can tell specific origin stories.
Pays significantly above commodity prices for high-quality, single-origin beans.
Demonstrates that consumers will pay more for ethical, traceable chocolate.
Drives innovation in fermentation and processing techniques that benefit farmers.
What it doesn't solve:
Value capture remains skewed. As one industry analysis notes, "most of the value is still being created — and captured — far from the farm." The premium price on craft chocolate goes largely toward processing and packaging in the Global North, not toward improving conditions at origin.
Scale is the problem. A small maker buying 1 bag of beans per year at a premium of $1,000/MT over what others pay creates impact that is, in concrete terms, negligible for the system.
It serves a wealthy demographic. The movement is predominantly a North American and European phenomenon, with 45% of market share in North America, catering to affluent, educated consumers willing to pay $8-15 per bar.
"Big Chocolate" co-optation. Large companies have adopted the term and acquired craft operations, diluting the movement's authenticity.
It doesn't address structural issues. The 2+ million farmers supplying mass-market chocolate — the ones with the worst labor conditions — are untouched by craft chocolate's direct-trade relationships.
The most honest critique came from within the movement itself: "It's also important for the two-ingredient school of the craft chocolate 'movement' to admit to itself and everyone else that nothing about it is actually revolutionary."

PART II: COFFEE
1. Shade-Grown vs. Sun-Grown Coffee
Coffee originated as an understory forest plant in the Ethiopian highlands. Beginning in the 1970s, technification programs encouraged conversion to full-sun cultivation for higher yields, fundamentally transforming the crop's relationship to landscapes.
Biodiversity impact: A 2024 meta-analysis in Science of the Total Environment found that coffee farms with high shade (>30%) harbor significantly higher species diversity than sun farms (0-5%). Insects, birds, mammals, and epiphytes benefit most from high shade. The Smithsonian Migratory Bird Center's review of 60+ studies found that shade-grown coffee is "the next best thing to natural forest." In southern Mexico, shade coffee farms support 180 bird species (46 migratory). In Venezuela, Bird Friendly-certified farms supported up to 14 times the density of migratory birds compared to primary forest.
Soil moisture in sun coffee farms can be 42% lower than in shade farms. Birds in shaded systems provide natural pest control — increased predation on coffee pests including the devastating coffee berry borer.
The yield question: The conventional view that shade reduces yields has been significantly complicated by recent research. A global review found that 57% of cases reported no trade-offs between yield and biodiversity in shade coffee farms. Yield reductions typically only become apparent when shade cover exceeds 30-50%. In Puerto Rico, researchers found no significant difference between shade and sun yields at the regional scale after isolating for planted area and region. Shade also improves bean quality, producing denser beans that command higher specialty prices.
In Central America, sun cultivation has destroyed 2.5 million acres of forest. In the Peruvian Amazon, shaded systems using Inga trees store approximately 118 tonnes/hectare of biomass carbon — nearly four times more than sun-grown monocultures (~31 t/ha).
The climate adaptation imperative: With up to 50% of land suitable for Arabica coffee potentially lost by 2050, shade systems are increasingly recognized as a nature-based adaptation strategy — buffering temperature extremes and maintaining microclimate conditions that Arabica requires.

2. Fair Trade vs. Direct Trade vs. Conventional
Fair Trade: Establishes a floor price (~15¢/lb above commodity rate) plus a 20¢/lb community development premium, with an additional 30¢/lb for organic certification. Fair Trade's share of bean sales has grown from 1.5% a decade ago to 6.0%.
The value capture problem: A study published in World Development found that of the approximately $1.50/lb premium consumers pay for Fair Trade coffee in U.S. supermarkets, most goes to the roaster's profit margin. The farmer receives about one-sixth of the consumer premium. Retailers actually make smaller absolute profits on Fair Trade coffee compared to conventional.
Direct Trade: Specialty companies build relationships directly with farmers or cooperatives, often paying 2-3x market rates for exceptional quality. Research from Colombia and Bolivia found that direct-trading schemes and farmer-owned roasting/selling operations produced the most beneficial income effects. However, participation requires significant economic and social capital, meaning "these value chains do not automatically benefit marginalized coffee producers and poor families."
Conventional commodity market: Farmers are largely price takers. The C-market (commodity futures price) determines what most farmers receive. When it drops — as it did by roughly half in the five years before 2019 — farmers face ruin regardless of the $6 lattes being sold downstream.

3. The Specialty Coffee Paradox
The global coffee economy generates over $495 billion annually (2023). What smallholder coffee growers receive does not even account for 10% of the value chain.
According to the International Trade Centre, producers retain approximately 10% of the retail coffee price — meaning that from a $4 filter coffee, about $0.40 reaches the farmer. Research from the Specialty Coffee Transaction Guide found that during the 2018-19 and 2019-20 Colombian harvests, less than 5% of specialty coffees scoring 80-83.9 points were traded above the living income price threshold.
The paradox deepens when you consider the structural barriers:
Farmers receive payment in one annual lump sum when they sell their harvest — this becomes their working capital for the entire following year. One bad weather event can be financially devastating.
Banks generally won't lend to farmers without extortionate interest rates.
The average income for a coffee farmer has not meaningfully changed in 20 years despite the industry's massive growth.
Simply paying more isn't sufficient — it could cause production surges, crop-switching, and renewed volatility.
What's needed is broader: income diversification, improved access to finance, agronomic knowledge, infrastructure investment, and fundamentally restructured value distribution.

4. Coffee's Water Footprint
The Water Footprint Network estimates the global average water footprint of a single 125ml cup of coffee at approximately 140 liters — more water than a 16-minute shower. This was corroborated by a 2003 UNESCO study.
The figure varies enormously by region: Vietnam achieves relatively low water consumption per tonne (6,054 m³/ton) due to efficiency, while some West African robusta producers like Togo (49,341 m³/ton) and Ghana (47,554 m³/ton) are at the extreme high end.
Notably, the difference between wet and dry processing is minimal — wet processing adds only about 0.34% to total water use. The overwhelming majority of water goes to growing the coffee plant itself.
Coffee processing also generates significant waste that frequently pollutes rivers — conventional wet milling produces effluent that devastates downstream water quality for communities. Techniques exist to dramatically reduce this (dry fermentation, effluent treatment), but they require investment the industry has been slow to provide.

5. Climate Change: Coffee's Existential Threat
Coffee faces potentially catastrophic climate disruption:
By 2050, the land area suitable for growing coffee may shrink by 48-97% in key regions. In Latin America, that figure could reach 88%.
47% of global coffee production comes from countries that could lose over 60% of their suitable coffee land by 2050 (World Coffee Research).
Around 8% of Arabica-growing areas are already climatically unsuitable, per Rabobank analysis. This could rise to 20% by 2050.
Arabica is particularly vulnerable — it requires a very narrow temperature range and is the species that produces 60-70% of world coffee.
Higher temperatures increase pest and disease pressure, including coffee leaf rust, which has already devastated Central American production.
Brazil, the world's largest producer, has experienced severe frost and drought events, and has little high-elevation land to which production could migrate.
The Robusta shift: Robusta, naturally more tolerant of heat, drought, and disease, is expanding into warmer, lower-altitude regions. In Ethiopia, suitable Arabica areas may actually increase from 39% to 50% by 2050 due to higher altitude availability — one of few bright spots.
Demand doubling, supply halving: Global demand for coffee is expected to roughly double by mid-century. Unless yields per hectare dramatically increase, coffee plantings would need to at least double — threatening some of the world's last remaining intact forests. Today, 60% of land that will be suitable for coffee in 2050 is currently forested, but only 20% of that forest is formally protected.

PART III: PALM OIL
1. Palm Oil's Ubiquity
Palm oil is in approximately 50% of all packaged products found in supermarkets, according to both the World Wildlife Fund and Palm Oil Investigations. This includes food products (pizza, doughnuts, chocolate, margarine, instant noodles, ice cream), personal care items (deodorant, shampoo, toothpaste, lipstick), cleaning products, and even pharmaceuticals. It is also increasingly used as a biofuel.
Palm oil and palm kernel oil account for 39% of global vegetable oil production — the largest share of any oil crop. In the 2022-23 marketing year, total global production was 77.56 million tonnes. Indonesia produced 46.50 Mt (59% of global supply) and Malaysia 18.39 Mt (24%), together accounting for 83% of the world market.
Production has increased roughly 40-fold since the 1970s, and annual supply increased by nearly 50 million tonnes between 1995 and 2015.

2. Deforestation Scale in Indonesia and Malaysia
Indonesia: Over 19 years (2001-2019), the area under oil palm doubled to 16.24 million hectares (64% industrial, 36% smallholder). Forest area declined by 11% (9.79 million hectares lost), including 3.09 million hectares (32% of total forest loss) ultimately converted to oil palm.
The expansion of oil palm plantations contributed approximately one-third of the total loss of old-growth forests in Indonesia over 20 years. Palm oil was the largest single driver of Indonesian deforestation from 2001-2016, peaking at nearly 40% in 2008-2009.
Indonesia achieved a remarkable reduction through 2021 — deforestation for palm oil fell to just 18% of its peak levels from a decade earlier. However, 2022 saw an 18% increase in deforestation linked to palm oil, and the trend has continued upward. In 2024, 122,000 hectares were lost within Indonesian oil palm concessions — and 67% of companies operating concessions recorded some deforestation.
At 2024 rates, Indonesia's palm oil concessions would be entirely cleared of remaining forest within 65 years.
Malaysia: Malaysia's trajectory has been different. Deforestation peaked in 2016 (19,000 hectares) and has declined to a stable level of approximately 6,000 hectares per year by 2024. Only 23% of companies recorded deforestation in 2024. However, only 12% of Malaysia's concession areas retain forest cover — there is simply less forest left to lose. Oil palm plantations occupy 15% of Malaysia's total land area and a staggering 66% of its agricultural land.
Peatland destruction: Palm oil's climate impact is amplified by plantation development on carbon-rich peatlands. Indonesia's palm oil sector emits approximately 220 million tonnes of greenhouse gases annually — nearly a fifth of the country's total emissions.

3. RSPO Certification: Does It Work?
The Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil (RSPO), established in 2004, is the primary sustainability certification scheme, with over 6,100 members in 105 countries and approximately 5.15 million hectares of certified area.
The evidence is deeply mixed:
Positive findings:
Research has found that RSPO-certified plantations have significantly lower levels of deforestation than non-certified ones.
Forest fires are significantly lower in certified plantations when fire likelihood is low.
A WCF-commissioned NORC study found that hazardous child labor was reduced by one-third in communities where company sustainability programs (including RSPO) are operating.
Negative findings and critiques:
Certified plantations tend to be older and with little remaining forested area — meaning certification may be credited for protection that reflects historical clearing rather than current restraint.
Research found "marginally small to no effects" of RSPO certification on avoided deforestation, fire occurrence, or orangutan population maintenance.
Certified plantations remain characterized by low landscape heterogeneity and biodiversity.
A satellite analysis revealed that palm oil areas certified as sustainable had in fact replaced tropical forests of Sumatra and Borneo, including critical habitat for endangered mammals.
Villages with RSPO-certified plantations experienced an overall reduction in well-being compared to villages with non-certified plantations — though this masked variation: established plantation areas (Sumatra) saw improvements, while subsistence-based areas (Kalimantan) did not.
Research published in Nature Communications Earth & Environment (2025) found that RSPO certification in Malaysia led to decreased plantation efficiency — an unintended consequence of compliance requirements.
Audit and governance problems:
Tracking implementation inside plantation sites has "low levels of reliability due to insufficient governance."
Auditors tend to dismiss evidence of non-compliance raised by local communities.
A 2013 investigation uncovered "flagrant disregard for human rights at some of the very plantations the RSPO certifies as 'sustainable.'"
A coalition of 100 environmental and human rights organizations (led by GRAIN) declared in 2022 that "19 years of deception and label fraud by the RSPO are enough," documenting ongoing cases where RSPO certified plantations in Africa despite community grievances about land grabbing, deforestation, pollution, and violence.
The RSPO took until 2018 to prohibit clearing of primary forests, and until 2017 to develop a clear Smallholder Standard.
Spillover effects: One particularly troubling finding: from 2009-2016, spillovers from RSPO certification reduced deforestation within Indonesia's forest estate but increased deforestation in areas zoned for agricultural use — suggesting displacement rather than prevention.

4. The Land Efficiency Argument
This is the counterintuitive case for palm oil, and it has genuine scientific backing:
Palm oil is by far the most productive vegetable oil crop, yielding 4-6 tonnes per hectare — dramatically outperforming soybean, sunflower, and rapeseed. Some estimates suggest palm produces up to 20 times as much oil per hectare as alternatives.
Palm oil accounts for 39% of global vegetable oil production but uses a relatively small share of total vegetable oil cropland. As Our World in Data's analysis frames it: "it's not clear that the alternatives would have fared any better. In fact, because we can produce up to 20 times as much oil per hectare from palm versus the alternatives, it has probably spared a lot of environmental impacts from elsewhere."
WWF and RSPO have echoed this: replacing palm oil with alternative oils would result in more deforestation and habitat conversion, not less, because vastly more land would be needed to produce equivalent volumes.
The critical caveat: This efficiency argument holds only if palm oil is grown on appropriate (non-forested, non-peat) land. The argument is about the crop being efficient, not about the practices being acceptable. The problem isn't that oil palm exists — it's that it has been planted by destroying some of the most biodiverse ecosystems on Earth, on carbon-dense peatlands, using exploitative labor.
The policy implication: Consumer boycotts of palm oil may be counterproductive. The more effective approach is demanding sustainably produced palm oil and holding certification schemes to higher standards. This is the position of WWF, IUCN, and many environmental scientists.

5. Smallholder vs. Industrial Plantations
Scale: In Indonesia, smallholder oil palm plantations cover approximately 5.82 million hectares — about 40% of total national oil palm area. Globally, millions of smallholder families depend on palm oil as their primary livelihood.
Deforestation attribution: The PLOS One satellite study found that industrial plantations replaced significantly more forest than smallholder plantings (2.13 million hectares vs. 0.72 million hectares in Indonesia 2001-2019). However, smallholder expansion is harder to monitor and regulate.
Certification barriers: RSPO certification for independent smallholders is extremely challenging. Research in Jambi, Indonesia found that most challenges of RSPO certification "are not well understood by smallholders," and that extensive external support from NGOs was the key factor enabling certification. Financial benefits of certification for smallholders can be small, and indirect/long-term benefits alone are insufficient motivation.
The equity paradox: Many critiques of RSPO note that it has "reified as 'sustainable' the industrial agro-business model on several thousands of hectares." The main biodiversity conservation gains would actually come from supporting smallholders rather than certifying industrial plantations — but smallholders are systematically excluded or underserved by certification schemes designed for large operators.
Palm oil has also lifted hundreds of thousands of people out of poverty — a fact often omitted from environmental critiques. Indigenous and rural communities in Borneo and Sumatra have experienced genuine economic improvement, even as they have lost forests. Research among Bornean villagers found that small-scale land clearing was viewed more positively than mass industrial deforestation — the conflict between economic development and ecological preservation does not have simple answers.

CROSS-CUTTING THEMES
The Voluntarism Trap
All three supply chains share a common structural pattern: voluntary industry commitments repeatedly fail to deliver promised results. The Harkin-Engel Protocol (cocoa), Fair Trade certification (coffee), and RSPO (palm oil) all demonstrate that market-based mechanisms alone cannot solve problems rooted in colonial-era power imbalances, extreme poverty, and structural extraction of value from the Global South.
The Consumer Premium Paradox
In all three commodities, consumer willingness to pay premiums for "ethical" products generates value — but that value is disproportionately captured by roasters, processors, retailers, and certification bodies in the Global North. The farmer at the base of the supply chain sees pennies of each premium dollar.
The Climate Convergence
All three crops face existential climate threats that also create perverse feedback loops: cocoa deforestation in West Africa accelerates regional warming; sun-grown coffee destroys the shade canopy needed for climate resilience; palm oil expansion onto peatlands releases massive greenhouse gases.
Regulation as the Missing Piece
The EU Deforestation Regulation (EUDR), despite implementation challenges, represents the first serious attempt to use trade law rather than voluntary commitments. Its effectiveness — or failure — will shape the trajectory of all three supply chains for the next decade.

Sources: NORC/University of Chicago (2020), Tulane University Payson Center reports (2007-2015), Environmental Research Letters meta-analyses, IUCN Oil Palm Task Force, WWF, Smithsonian Migratory Bird Center, Water Footprint Network, Trase/University of California Santa Barbara, Satelligence, International Coffee Organization, Specialty Coffee Association, Tony's Chocolonely FAIR reports, RSPO, Rainforest Rescue/GRAIN coalition, Verité, World Coffee Research, and peer-reviewed research published in Nature, PLOS One, Science of the Total Environment, World Development, and Frontiers in Sustainable Food Systems.
