1. Food Waste Scale: The UNEP Picture
In 2022, the world wasted 1.05 billion metric tons of food, amounting to about one-fifth (19%) of food available to consumers at the retail, food service, and household levels. That's on top of the 13% of the world's food lost in the supply chain (post-harvest up to retail), as estimated by FAO — so roughly a third of all food produced never gets eaten.
The distribution is striking: households were responsible for 631 million metric tons (60%), with food service at 290 million tons and retail at 131 million tons. The per capita figure lands at 132 kilograms per person per year.
One of the most important findings: food waste is not just a "rich country" problem. High-income, upper-middle income, and lower-middle income countries differ in observed average levels of household food waste by just 7 kg/capita/year. The U.S. picture is somewhat inverted — based on EPA data from 2019, 40% of the 66.2 million tons of wasted food was generated by households and 60% from food service and food retail.
The climate stakes are severe: food loss and waste generates 8% to 10% of global greenhouse gas emissions — almost five times the total emissions from the aviation sector. The moral dimension is equally stark: over one billion meals are discarded daily while 783 million people are hungry and a third of humanity faces food insecurity.
On hopeful notes: countries such as Japan and the UK show that change at scale is possible, with reductions of 18% and 31% respectively.

2. Landfill Methane from Food Waste
The EPA data here is damning. Municipal solid waste landfills are the third-largest source of methane emissions from human activities in the United States. Food waste comprises about 24 percent of municipal solid waste disposed of in landfills. Because of food's rapid decomposition under anaerobic conditions, an estimated 58 percent of the fugitive methane emissions from municipal solid waste landfills are from landfilled food waste.
The timing problem is critical: since fifty percent of the carbon in food waste is degraded to landfill gas within 3.6 years, improving gas collection system efficiency in later years cannot substantially reduce these emissions — the methane escapes before gas capture systems are even installed. An estimated 61 percent of methane generated by landfilled food waste is not captured by landfill gas collection systems.
The scale in the U.S.: In 2020, food waste was responsible for approximately 55 million metric tons of CO₂ equivalents from U.S. MSW landfills. ReFED's more recent analysis found that 23 million tons of surplus food were sent to landfill in 2024, releasing over 600,000 metric tons of methane.
Is the Drawdown "#1 solution" claim accurate? It's nuanced. Food waste reduction remains the #1 solution under the scenario that limits end-of-century warming to 2°C. In the more ambitious scenario limiting warming to 1.5°C, projections for dramatic electrification and grid decarbonization put Onshore Wind and Utility-Scale Solar at #1 and #2 — Reducing Food Waste comes in at #4, just after Plant-Rich Diet. Importantly, Drawdown's updated Explorer tool no longer ranks individual climate solutions over each other but instead categorizes them. Reducing food loss and waste is classified as "Highly Recommended" and categorized as an "emergency brake" solution for climate change — meaning it delivers rapid atmospheric benefits because methane is short-lived compared to CO₂. The potential impact is estimated at 1.23 to 4.94 gigatonnes of CO₂e reduction per year.
So: calling food waste reduction "the #1 climate solution" is a defensible shorthand under the 2°C scenario but oversimplifies the updated analysis, which deliberately avoids rankings and treats different scenarios differently.

3. Composting Science
Composting methods vary enormously in temperature, throughput, and what they can handle:
Home composting operates at ambient temperatures (mesophilic range, roughly 20–45°C). It works well for fruit/vegetable scraps, coffee grounds, eggshells, yard waste, and uncoated paper. It typically cannot process meat, dairy, oils, or pet waste safely due to insufficient heat to kill pathogens, and takes 3–12 months. Most "commercially compostable" packaging will not break down in a backyard pile.
Municipal/industrial composting reaches thermophilic temperatures (55–70°C) through managed aeration and turning, processing material in weeks rather than months. These facilities can handle meat, dairy, cooked food, and certified compostable packaging. The high heat kills pathogens and weed seeds, producing stable, safe compost.
Anaerobic digestion processes organic waste in sealed, oxygen-free reactors, producing biogas (primarily methane and CO₂) that can generate electricity or be upgraded to renewable natural gas, plus a nutrient-rich digestate. It's particularly effective for wet, high-energy feedstocks like food waste. Diverting 75% of the food waste landfilled in one year in the United States to a composting facility or anaerobic digester would drive an 80–90% emissions reduction over the waste's lifetime compared with landfilling.
Vermicomposting uses red wiggler worms (Eisenia fetida) to process organic material at ambient temperatures. It produces high-quality worm castings rich in plant-available nutrients and beneficial microorganisms, but handles relatively small volumes and is limited to non-acidic, non-oily food scraps.
On carbon sequestration: compost applied to soil builds stable organic carbon, improves water retention, and reduces the need for synthetic fertilizers. Single applications can increase soil carbon storage by 25–70% over decades. The Marin Carbon Project and similar research has shown that even a thin application of compost to rangeland measurably increases soil carbon for years afterward.

4. "Compostable" Packaging: Label vs. Reality
This is where the gap between marketing and infrastructure is widest.
The standards: BPI certification in North America requires products to meet ASTM D6400 (plastics) or D6868 (coatings), meaning they must disintegrate and biodegrade within a defined timeframe in industrial composting conditions (sustained 55–60°C). Europe's equivalent is EN 13432. Products may no longer be claimed as BPI-certified unless they meet all conditions including no intentionally-added fluorinated chemicals and a test report showing less than 100 ppm total organic fluorine.
The home compost gap: Historically, BPI certification applied specifically to industrial composting environments, which operate under controlled conditions not typically available in home compost systems. This is changing — BPI launched its Commercial & Home Compostable Certification program in September 2025, officially accepting applications from December 1, 2025. The home certification is based on the French Standard NF T 51-800 and requires products to break down at lower backyard temperatures.
The landfill problem: Compostable packaging in a landfill behaves like any organic material — it decomposes anaerobically and produces methane, just like the food waste it was designed to accompany. The whole premise of compostable packaging is that it travels with food scraps into a composting stream, not that it somehow degrades benignly in a landfill.
The infrastructure gap is enormous: Only 10% of U.S. households have access to organics recycling through drop-off and curbside organics collection programs, and only 4% of wasted food is sent to composters today. Even within that 10%, many composting facilities can't process all compostable materials — some only accept yard waste, excluding food scraps, and many composting facilities still do not accept compostable packaging. According to the EPA, it will take over $14 billion to build the infrastructure required to bridge the gap.
California's SB 1383 is the most aggressive U.S. mandate, requiring local governments to provide organic waste recycling or composting services to all residents and businesses with a target of diverting 75% of organic waste by 2025. New York City rolled out mandatory citywide curbside composting by October 2024, but early results were modest — the citywide capture rate for organics was 3.7% in fiscal year 2024, with food scraps only 1.2%.

5. Packaging LCA: Material by Material
Recycling rates vary dramatically by material and by geography:
Aluminum: Infinitely recyclable without quality loss. 43% of aluminum beverage cans shipped in the U.S. in 2023 were recycled — the lowest rate since tracking began in 1990. However, the closed-loop circularity rate is 96.7%, and aluminum beverage cans contain 71% recycled content. Recycled aluminum saves 94% of the carbon and 93% of the energy needed to make new aluminum. EU metallic packaging recycling stands at about 75%.
Glass: Also infinitely recyclable without degradation. But the US glass recycling rate is about 31% — strikingly low because glass is heavy, costly to transport, and often breaks in single-stream recycling, contaminating other materials. The EU's average glass packaging collection rate in 2022 was 80.2%, largely thanks to deposit-return systems. Glass bottle recycling rates are 63% in DRS states compared to just 24% in non-DRS states.
Paper/Cardboard: Paper and cardboard packaging had the highest recycling rate in the EU in 2022, at 83.2%. In the U.S., corrugated cardboard achieves about 91%, but overall paper recycling is around 68%. Paper degrades with each recycling cycle, though research shows that paper fiber can be recycled 25 times with high quality, significantly more than previous estimates of 4 to 7 times.
Plastic: The bleakest picture. Globally, only 9% of plastic waste was recycled in 2019; 19% was incinerated, almost 50% went to landfills, and 22% was mismanaged. The U.S. is worse — of the 40 million tons of plastic waste generated in 2021, only 5% to 6% was recycled. EU plastic packaging recycling is around 40–41%. Different resins have radically different recyclability: PET (#1) and HDPE (#2) are the most recycled; PS (#6), multi-layer films, and mixed plastics are essentially unrecyclable at scale.
Multi-layer packaging (Tetra Paks, chip bags, pouches): These are the hardest to recycle because they fuse aluminum, plastic, and paper into inseparable layers. Tetra Pak claims recycling rates of 26% globally, but this varies enormously by country. Metallized film chip bags and squeezable pouches are functionally non-recyclable in most municipal systems. Flexible packaging, despite being the second largest packaging segment in the U.S. at $41.5 billion in sales, presents severe end-of-life challenges.
Steel: The most recycled food container material in the U.S. at about 58%, and reaching 80.5% in Europe, a new record.

6. Deposit-Return Systems
DRS programs consistently outperform all other collection methods:
Germany (Pfand): The return rate for single-use plastic bottles reached 97.7% in 2024, with a €0.25 deposit on single-use containers. 42% of all beverages are filled in refillable containers. However, there's an important caveat noted in the literature: no single agency in Germany collects data on how many beverage containers are sold and redeemed each year, so a precise redemption rate cannot be calculated — the widely cited 98% figure comes from limited data. Still, all indicators point to extraordinary performance.
Paradoxically, single-use plastic bottles now account for 71% of the German market compared with 40% a decade ago — the deposit system incentivizes return but hasn't prevented a shift from reusable to single-use.
Scandinavia: Norway achieves 92% return rates, with less than 1% of drink containers littered. Lithuania jumped from a return rate below 34% before its deposit system to 92% just two years later. Hungary's system achieved an 88.8% return rate in 2025, collecting over 3 billion containers.
Oregon Bottle Bill (U.S.): One of the oldest DRS programs (1971). U.S. states with DRS achieve dramatically higher rates: the 10 states with DRS boast an average aluminum can recycling rate of 68% compared to 22% in non-DRS states.
EU-wide mandate: The EU's Packaging and Packaging Waste Regulation, voted into law in December 2024, requires each member state to implement a deposit system for cans and plastic bottles by 2029 to achieve 90% separate collection. Ireland, which launched its DRS in February 2024, achieved a 73% return rate within seven months.

7. Microplastics from Food Packaging (2024–2025 Research)
This has been one of the fastest-moving research areas. A landmark systematic review published in June 2025 in NPJ Science of Food by Zimmermann et al. at the Food Packaging Forum reviewed 103 scientific studies and found that 96% of tested food packaging released detectable amounts of microplastics into packaged products.
Key mechanisms: the abrasion from repeatedly opening and closing the caps on glass and plastic bottles can release an untold amount of micro- and nanoplastics into the beverage. Researchers found particles in beer, canned fish, rice, mineral water, tea bags, table salts, take-out foods and soft drinks. One study found an average of 240,000 plastic particles in a single liter of bottled water.
A surprising finding from a separate French study (ANSES): across all the beverages tested, the highest number of particles were found in glass bottles — about 100 microplastic particles per liter, five to 50 times more than in plastic bottles or cans. The explanation? All of the glass bottles they tested except wine bottles had metal caps decorated with polyester paint that matched the color and material of the particles found. The contamination dropped by more than half when caps were rinsed before bottling.
Ultra-processed foods present an additional pathway: processed foods pass through a complicated web of conveyor belts and machines — with many parts made of plastic — before being packaged, so exposure may begin before the consumer even handles the product.
Health implications are still being established, but a March 2024 study in the New England Journal of Medicine found that people with plastic particles in their arteries were twice as likely to have a heart attack, stroke or die early compared to those without them. The EFSA has published a literature review acknowledging the release is real but cautioning that many so-called microplastic particles detected are actually mimics such as fatty acids or oligomers that precipitate during testing, calling for better standardized methods.

8. Date Labeling and Food Waste
This is possibly the most fixable dimension of the entire problem. Food manufacturers use a variety of phrases such as "Sell By," "Use By" and "Best By" on product labels on a voluntary basis, and there are over 50 non-standardized date label phrases in use in the U.S. The only federal requirement is for infant formula.
The key distinction consumers miss: "Best if Used By" indicates quality (flavor, texture at peak), while "Use By" should indicate safety. Almost no date labels on commercial food (except infant formula) are safety dates — yet 84% of consumers toss out food at least some of the time because of the date label, and 37% do it most of the time. A 2025 survey found 88 percent of consumers discard food near the package labeling date at least occasionally.
The cost: It has been estimated that confusion over date labeling accounts for approximately 20 percent of consumer food waste. More concretely, in 2023, Americans wasted over 3 billion pounds or approximately $7 billion worth of food due to date label confusion alone. The USDA estimates the average family of four spends at least $1,500 annually on food that goes uneaten.
In the EU, roughly 10%, or 88 million tonnes, of food waste in the European Union is linked to date marking. The EU has been considering removing "best before" dates from certain long-shelf-life products.
California passed a law requiring standardization to just two consumer-facing phrases. In December 2024, the FDA and USDA jointly issued a Request for Information on date labeling practices, signaling potential federal action. The proposed Food Date Labeling Act (S.1484/H.R.3159) would standardize labels nationally to "Best If Used By" (quality) and "Use By" (safety). Standardizing date labels would have a net financial benefit of $3.8 billion per year, the large majority of which would be savings to consumers.

Synthesis: The System Failure
What emerges from this research is a picture of multiple interdependent failures — not a single broken link. Food waste is the most impactful by volume and climate effect but the least attended-to in policy. Packaging designed to be "compostable" arrives in a country where 90% of households lack composting access. Deposit-return systems prove behavioral economics works brilliantly (Germany's near-total return rates vs. the U.S.'s 31% glass recycling), but the U.S. has only implemented them in 10 states. Microplastics research is revealing that the problem isn't just end-of-life but use-of-life — the simple act of opening and closing a container. And the most cost-effective intervention of all — standardizing two phrases on food labels — has been stuck in voluntary limbo for over a decade.
The through-line for your book's argument about "grammars" is that we have the technologies (composting, anaerobic digestion, deposit systems, standardized labeling) but not the coordinating structures — the shared rules, the infrastructure investment, the political will — to deploy them at the scale the crisis demands. The fire is acquired; the grammar for tending it is not.

Foundational Datasets for Food Environmental Impact
A Research Compendium

1. Poore & Nemecek (2018) — The Cornerstone Meta-Analysis
Citation: Poore, J. & Nemecek, T. (2018). "Reducing food's environmental impacts through producers and consumers." Science, 360(6392), 987–992.
Scope and Method
This study remains the largest meta-analysis of global food systems ever conducted. It consolidated life cycle assessment (LCA) data from 570 published studies (2000–2016), covering approximately 38,700 commercially viable farms across 119 countries, plus 1,600 processors, packaging types, and retailers. It assessed 40 agricultural goods representing roughly 90% of global dietary energy and protein intake, across five environmental indicators:
Greenhouse gas emissions (kg CO₂-equivalents, using GWP100)
Land use (m² per year)
Terrestrial acidification (g SO₂-equivalents)
Eutrophication (g PO₄-equivalents)
Scarcity-weighted freshwater withdrawals
The system boundary runs from extraction of agricultural inputs through to retail, including land use change, on-farm emissions, fertilizer and pesticide production, processing, transport, packaging, and retail.
Key Findings
The food system's total footprint: The global food supply chain generates approximately 13.7 billion metric tons of CO₂eq annually, representing about 26% of anthropogenic GHG emissions. An additional 2.8 billion tons (5%) comes from non-food agriculture and other deforestation drivers.
Land use: Approximately 43% of the Earth's ice- and desert-free land is used for agriculture, with 83% of agricultural land devoted to animal-sourced foods.
The 50-fold variation: Perhaps the study's most consequential finding is that environmental impact can vary 50-fold among producers of the same product. This enormous heterogeneity means that a small number of high-impact producers drive a disproportionate share of damage — and also that targeting those producers creates major mitigation opportunities.
Animal vs. plant products: Even the lowest-impact animal products typically exceed the environmental impacts of vegetable substitutes. This finding holds across all five indicators and provides strong evidence for the importance of dietary change.
Supply chain breakdown: For most foods, land use change and farm-stage emissions dominate the footprint. Transport typically accounts for less than 1% of beef's GHG emissions and under 10% for most products — meaning what you eat matters far more than where it comes from.
Dietary shift potential: Moving from current diets to one excluding animal products could reduce food's land use by ~76%, GHG emissions by ~49%, acidification by ~50%, eutrophication by ~49%, and scarcity-weighted freshwater withdrawals by ~19%. An additional reduction of ~5.5 billion tons of CO₂ could come from carbon sequestration on abandoned pasture.
Critiques and Limitations
Marginal land argument: The study has been criticized for not adequately accounting for beef production on land unsuitable for crops. Pastoral systems on marginal rangeland may have lower opportunity costs than the global averages suggest.
Functional unit sensitivity: Results shift depending on whether impacts are measured per kg, per calorie, per gram of protein, or per portion. Nutrient-dense foods like cheese appear differently across these metrics.
Geographic bias in underlying LCAs: The 570 source studies skew somewhat toward higher-income countries, though the authors validated representativeness against FAOSTAT yield data.
Static snapshot: The 2000–2016 data window doesn't capture more recent shifts in production practices, precision agriculture, or methane-reduction technologies.
Methane metric debate: Using GWP100 for methane is standard but debated. Methane's shorter atmospheric lifetime (~12 years vs. centuries for CO₂) means GWP100 may overstate beef's long-term warming contribution relative to CO₂-intensive foods — though even excluding methane entirely, beef's footprint (~36 kg CO₂eq/kg) remains roughly four times that of chicken.
Erratum: A 2019 correction (Science 363: eaaw9908) addressed errors in the original supplementary data.
Subsequent Validation
The EDGAR-FOOD database (Crippa et al., 2021, Nature Food) independently estimated food system emissions at 18 Gt CO₂eq/year (34% of total anthropogenic emissions in 2015), broadly consistent with Poore & Nemecek's estimate. The European Commission's IDEA dataset (2019, updated 2021–2023) mapped the 43 Poore & Nemecek commodities onto 4,089 FoodEx2 food terms, becoming the basis for FAO/WHO GIFT dietary environmental infographics.

2. Hannah Ritchie / Our World in Data + Not the End of the World (2024)
Our World in Data: The Food Section
Hannah Ritchie (Deputy Editor and Science Outreach Lead at Our World in Data, and researcher at the Oxford Martin Programme in Global Development) has built what is arguably the most influential public-facing data communication platform for food-environment research. The Environmental Impacts of Food Data Explorer is sourced primarily from Poore & Nemecek (2018) and presents interactive comparisons across GHG emissions, land use, water use, and eutrophication for dozens of food products.
Key OWID contributions to public understanding:
"Eat local" is mostly a myth: Transport accounts for just ~5% of food system emissions globally; for high-impact foods like beef, it's under 1%. Ritchie demonstrates that substituting less than one day per week of beef and dairy calories with chicken, fish, or plant-based alternatives achieves greater emissions reductions than buying everything locally.
Animal size correlates with footprint: A rough hierarchy emerges consistently: beef > lamb > pork > chicken > fish > eggs, with plant-based foods at the bottom.
Land use dominance: The visualization that 77% of agricultural land is used for livestock (including feed crops) while providing only 18% of global calories and 37% of protein has become one of the most-cited infographics in food sustainability discourse.
Not the End of the World (January 2024)
Ritchie's book tackles seven environmental crises (air pollution, climate change, deforestation, food, biodiversity loss, ocean plastics, overfishing) through a data-driven lens, explicitly pushing back against "doomerism."
Key arguments challenging common assumptions:
Progress is real and measurable: CO₂ emissions per capita appear to have peaked globally; growth is decoupling from emissions; renewable energy prices are driving transformation. The point is not complacency but recognizing that trajectory matters.


The biggest food levers are few and clear: (a) Eat less meat and dairy, especially beef; (b) reduce food waste and losses; (c) increase crop yields in sub-Saharan Africa (where the largest population growth will occur, and where low yields drive deforestation).


Sustainability requires lifting people out of poverty: True sustainability has two dimensions — protecting future environments and meeting current human needs. Low crop yields in sub-Saharan Africa are both a humanitarian and environmental crisis because they drive agricultural expansion into forests.


Skepticism toward depopulation and degrowth narratives: Global population growth rates have been falling for decades; the world is not growing exponentially. Degrowth frameworks often underestimate the technological progress already underway.


Interdependencies are an opportunity: Environmental problems overlap — renewable energy simultaneously addresses air pollution and climate change; increasing yields addresses both food security and deforestation.


Critiques of Ritchie's approach:
Reviewers at Crooked Timber note she is largely silent on redistribution, doughnut economics (Kate Raworth), and the Sustainable Development Goals.
The optimism framework can understate the difficulty of political implementation and the agency of powerful interests resisting change.
Simon Maxwell observed she has only one reference to circular economy principles and doesn't engage deeply with "regenerative by design" thinking.
The book does not substantially address ultra-processed food concerns (which Chris Van Tulleken's work has popularized) or the corporate consolidation of food systems.

3. Water Footprint Network — Green, Blue, and Grey Water
The Framework
The Water Footprint Network (WFN), founded on the work of Arjen Hoekstra (University of Twente), developed the three-component water footprint framework:
Green water: Rainwater absorbed by soil and used by crops (soil moisture). This is the dominant component for most agriculture.
Blue water: Surface water and groundwater consumed through irrigation. This is the component most directly linked to water scarcity.
Grey water: The volume of freshwater required to dilute pollutants (mainly nitrogen from fertilizers) to meet water quality standards.
