Context Dependence — Why Totals Can Mislead
The critical insight from the WFN framework is that not all water is equal:
Green water (rainwater) is generally non-rivalrous — it would fall whether or not a crop were planted. A high green water footprint for grass-fed beef in a wet climate is ecologically very different from the same total in an arid region.
Blue water is where scarcity bites. Nuts (especially almonds) have the highest blue water requirements at ~1,367 m³/ton, while roots and tubers need only ~16 m³/ton. California's almond industry became a flashpoint during the state's historic drought precisely because of this blue water intensity.
Grey water signals pollution load. Industrial feedlot beef has a much higher grey water footprint than pasture systems due to concentrated manure runoff.
The water footprint of 200g of beef equals about 47 eight-minute showers and uses four times more water than the same amount of chicken. Global animal production requires approximately 2,422 Gm³ of water per year (87.2% green, 6.2% blue, 6.6% grey).
The Poore & Nemecek dataset uses scarcity-weighted freshwater withdrawals, which weights blue water use by local water stress — a meaningful refinement over raw volume comparisons.

4. IPCC AR6 — Food Systems and Climate
Food's Climate Contribution
The IPCC Special Report on Climate Change and Land (2019) estimated food system emissions at 21–37% of global total anthropogenic GHG emissions (10.8–19.1 Gt CO₂eq/year). The subsequent EDGAR-FOOD database (Crippa et al., 2021) placed the figure at 34% (18 Gt CO₂eq) for 2015, with a 95% confidence interval of 14–22 Gt.
Breakdown of food system emissions:
71% from agriculture and associated land use/land-use change (LULUC)
29% from supply chain activities: retail, transport, consumption, fuel production, waste management, industrial processes, packaging
CO₂ accounts for roughly half of food-related emissions
Methane (CH₄) makes up ~35%, mainly from livestock, rice cultivation, and waste treatment
Nitrous oxide (N₂O) from fertilizers and manure constitutes most of the remainder
Developing countries (including China) emit 73% of food system GHG; industrialized countries emit 27%. However, in industrialized countries, pre- and post-production processes (processing, retail, packaging, household consumption) make up over half of food emissions — whereas in Africa and South America these are only 12–14%.
AR6 Mitigation Strategies for Food
The IPCC AR6 Working Group III (2022) identifies food systems as one of the most cost-effective and readily available mitigation sectors, with key strategies including:
Demand-side shifts: Shifting to sustainable healthy diets and reducing food loss/waste. These can reduce ecosystem conversion and methane/nitrous oxide emissions while freeing land for reforestation and ecosystem restoration.


Sustainable agricultural intensification: Increasing yields (especially in sub-Saharan Africa) without expanding agricultural land.


Improved farm management: Better manure and fertilizer management, improved feeds and feeding techniques to reduce enteric methane, rotational grazing for soil carbon storage.


Agroecological principles: Ecosystem-based management, farm and landscape diversification, agroforestry — these support food security, biodiversity, and carbon sequestration simultaneously.


Food waste reduction: Over 1 billion tons of food (17% of all food available to consumers) is wasted annually, contributing 8–10% of global GHG emissions. If food waste were a country, it would be the third-largest emitter.


The AR6 Synthesis Report (2023) emphasizes that these options are "feasible, effective, and low-cost" and that overlapping environmental problems can be tackled simultaneously due to their interdependencies.
Climate Impacts on Food Systems (Feedback Loop)
Human-induced warming has already slowed agricultural productivity growth over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes. Under high-emission scenarios, over 30% of current global crop and livestock areas could become climatically unsuitable by 2100 (vs. below 8% under aggressive mitigation). Increased, potentially concurrent climate extremes will periodically trigger simultaneous losses in major food-producing regions.

5. EAT-Lancet Planetary Health Diet
What It Recommends
The EAT-Lancet Commission (2019, updated 2025) convened 37 experts from 35 countries to define a universal reference diet optimizing human health within planetary boundaries. The Planetary Health Diet (PHD) is a flexitarian, predominantly plant-based pattern:
Base: Vegetables, fruits, whole grains, legumes, nuts, unsaturated oils
Moderate amounts: Fish, shellfish, poultry, dairy, eggs
Minimal: Red meat (beef, lamb, pork), processed meat, added sugars, refined grains, starchy vegetables
Practical guidance from co-chair Walter Willett: limiting dairy to about once daily, red meat to about once weekly, and eggs/poultry/fish to approximately twice weekly fits within the PHD pattern — resembling the Mediterranean diet.
Estimated Impacts
Health: Universal adoption could prevent up to 15 million premature deaths per year (up from 11 million in the 2019 estimate), mainly through reduced coronary heart disease, stroke, type-2 diabetes, and some cancers.
Climate: A total global shift to the PHD combined with strong cross-sector climate policy could reduce food system GHG from 7.35 to 2.75 Gt CO₂eq — equivalent to eliminating all coal-fired power plant emissions globally.
Land: A 7% reduction in agricultural land use, enabling biodiversity restoration.
Critiques
Cultural bias and equity (the dominant critique):
The 2019 report was criticized for insufficient attention to cultural food preferences, agricultural livelihoods, and affordability. The cost of following the PHD would have exceeded per-capita income for nearly a quarter of the world's population. Even the minimum-cost version was more expensive than baseline nutrient adequacy in many low-income countries.
Italy's UN representative argued that a single global dietary approach would threaten traditional diets and cultural heritage; the WHO withdrew sponsorship of an EAT-Lancet event.
Critics have described the original framing as reflecting a Eurocentric view of health, and the 2019 report was notably absent on the role of indigenous foods.
The meat industry funded astroturfing campaigns (via "Red Flag" consultancy) to portray the report as radical and culturally insensitive, which successfully blunted its policy impact, even among sustainability-minded experts who became reluctant to cite it.
Micronutrient concerns:
A 2023 study in Lancet Planetary Health found that the PHD, as specified, showed shortfalls in vitamin B12, calcium, iron, and zinc — especially for women of reproductive age. The diet's high phytate content (>2,400 mg) reduces zinc and iron bioavailability below levels assumed in the original adequacy assessment.
The original report assumed moderately to highly active individuals, which may overestimate caloric (and thus micronutrient) intake for sedentary populations.
The 2025 Update: The updated Commission directly responded to these critiques with greater flexibility in reference values, potential exchanges between food groups, adaptation to diverse cultural foodways (indigenous diets, Mediterranean diet, grain-tuber-legume diets), expanded 35-country representation, and a central focus on equity, justice, and fair working conditions. However, critics note that without local stakeholder voices, even "flexibility" may not bridge the gap for populations whose baseline diets are very different from the PHD.

6. NOVA Ultra-Processed Food Classification
The Classification System
Developed by Carlos Augusto Monteiro and colleagues in Brazil (2009, refined through 2019), NOVA classifies all foods into four groups by degree of industrial processing:
Group 1 (G1): Unprocessed or minimally processed foods (fruits, vegetables, grains, legumes, meat, milk, eggs)
Group 2 (G2): Processed culinary ingredients (oils, butter, sugar, salt, flour)
Group 3 (G3): Processed foods (canned vegetables, cheese, bread, cured meats)
Group 4 (G4): Ultra-processed foods (UPFs) — industrially manufactured products with additives like emulsifiers, flavoring, coloring; includes soft drinks, packaged snacks, instant noodles, reconstituted meat products, frozen ready meals
Environmental Correlation: Complex, Not Simple
The relationship between NOVA processing level and environmental impact is more nuanced than commonly assumed:
Evidence suggesting UPFs worsen environmental impact:
A 30-year Brazilian study (da Silva et al., 2021, Lancet Planetary Health) found that as UPF consumption increased, environmental footprints worsened: UPF-associated GHG emissions rose 245%, water footprint rose 233%, and ecological footprint rose 183% over the period. Ultra-processed meat was the primary driver, roughly doubling its contribution to daily environmental impacts and reaching ~20% of total diet-related footprints.
UPFs often rely on monoculture commodity crops (soy, corn, palm oil, sugar) whose expansion drives deforestation and biodiversity loss.
Packaging from UPFs accounts for about half of total food packaging by weight and nearly two-thirds of packaging waste by volume (in the US).
Long international transport routes for ingredients and finished products increase fossil fuel use.
Evidence that the relationship is more complicated:
Belgian research (Dénos et al., 2024) found that despite providing ~50% of calories, UPFs contributed proportionally less to overall resource use than their caloric share — 50% of climate impact, 41% of water use, 38% of fossil resource scarcity. Unprocessed foods (G1), especially red meat, beverages, and produce, generated disproportionately large impacts relative to their caloric contribution.
A scoping review of 15 years of NOVA literature (PMC, 2025) found that while most studies showed synergistic relationships between UPF consumption and GHG emissions (8 of 13 studies), the relationship with blue water footprint was actually discordant in the majority of cases — meaning higher UPF intake was associated with lower water consumption in many contexts.
UPF manufacturing can maximize efficiency, reduce food waste, and optimize shelf life, potentially lowering per-unit environmental burdens through supply chain optimization.
Critics argue that NOVA's binary classification fails to distinguish between nutritionally harmful UPFs (sugary drinks, ultra-processed meats) and benign or beneficial ones (fortified cereals, plant-based protein alternatives). The transition to more plant-based diets will require food technology that NOVA would classify as "ultra-processing."
The core tension: NOVA is fundamentally a health classification, not an environmental one. It tracks processing intensity, but environmental impact is primarily driven by what raw materials are used, not how much they are processed. A grass-fed steak (G1) has a vastly higher environmental footprint than a soy-based burger (G4). This creates a genuine paradox for policy: the healthiest-for-the-planet dietary shifts may require more, not less, food processing.

